Besides, the concentration of BPHA CDs was also studied. As demonstrated in Fig. S4, the detection of Cu2+ was significantly influenced by the concentration of BPHA CDs. The value of (F0
                        –F) increased with the increasing concentration of BPHA CDs up to 15.52 μg mL−1, then decreased when the concentration was over 15.52 μg mL−1. Intriguingly, with the concentration of PPi increased, the value of (F’–F0
                        ) reached the maximum value at 15.52 μg mL−1 of BPHA CDs and decreased slightly thereafter. Thus, 15.52 μg mL−1 of BPHA CDs was chosen as the optimal concentration for the detection.

Then the effect of pH of BPHA CDs on the (F0
                        –F) value with the addition of Cu2+ and (F’–F0
                        ) value with the addition of PPi was investigated. As shown in Fig. S5, the (F0
                        –F) value increased to the maximum value with the increase of pH up to 7.4 and later decreased. The (F’–F0
                        ) value demonstrated similar trends, increasing first, decreasing later and reaching the maximum value at pH of 7.4. To sum up, 15.52 μg mL−1 of BPHA CDs was chosen as the optimal concentration for the detection of Cu2+ and PPi at pH 7.4.

The color change and absorption of BPHA CDs/Cu2+ with PV and PPi was monitored (Fig. 11
                         and Fig. S10). PV is a typical indicator which can exhibit obvious color change from yellow to blue when it binds with metal complex while the addition of PPi can recover the original color [52]. Clear color changes from colorless to blue for BPHA CDs/Cu2+ and blue to gray for BPHA CDs/Cu2+–PV were observed by naked eyes when PV and PPi was added, respectively (see Fig. 11), indicating binding of PV with BPHA CDs/Cu2+ and replacement of PV by PPi, whereas BPHA CDs alone exhibited no obvious color changes with the addition of PV or PV and PPi together in comparison with PV. These were in accordance with corresponding changes in the UV/Vis absorption spectra, in which the λmax changed from 444 nm to 627 nm for BPHA CDs/Cu2+ and 607 nm to 444 nm for BPHA CDs/Cu2+/PV (see Fig. 12
                        ). As illustrated in Scheme 1, BPHA CDs/Cu2+ first binds with PV forming a reversible noncovalent complex, then a competitive analyte (PPi) displaces PV from BPHA CDs/Cu2+/PV. By contrast, no obvious color change and absorption spectra change were observed upon the addition of other anions (Fig. S11 and Fig. S12), confirming the high selectivity of BPHA CDs/Cu2+ for PPi.
